[{"id":27001,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["benzoic acid","salicylaldehyde","salicylic acid","phthalic acid"],"answer":2,"solution":"Kolbe - Schmidt reaction is\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/WE8gRSYWKXuWFIld9WGfULK0gzIuq-HZTSdHqf8PX4U.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":26921,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Both (A) and (R) are correct and (R)&nbsp;is the correct explanation of (A).","(A) is true but (R)&nbsp;is false.","Both (A) and (R) are correct but (R)&nbsp;is not the correct explanation of (A).","(A) is false but (R)&nbsp;is true."],"answer":2,"solution":"In electrolytic reduction of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> we use cryolite to increase conductivity and decrease melting point. Cryolyte is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>AIF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;Oxidation number of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Al</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26911,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d08de57e-17b4-4a01-aa8d-d4eddaa50729-9726782.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 447px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26907,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect.","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect."],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Phenols are much more acidic than alcohols because the negative charge in the phenoxide ion is not localized on the oxygen atom as it is in an alkoxide ion but is delocalised as it is shared by a number of carbon atoms in the benzene ring.</p>Phenol are weakly acidic. Phenol is more acidic than alcohol &amp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> statement (I) is correct. (II) is incorrect.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26887,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/25bdc9fc-6e8b-46e6-b65a-38f297655c2e-9894605_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 150px;\" /></p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/30e4922c-ef25-441b-b537-3a4d3c6ad3e4-9894605_2.PNG\" style=\"width: 132px; height: 150px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8e6fb103-e008-4520-9aee-20583ebba31e-9894605_3.PNG\" style=\"width: 136px; height: 150px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2ac0f4a9-00d5-4920-a851-338735907ad4-9894605_4.PNG\" style=\"width: 141px; height: 150px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Alcohol forms carbocation inthe presence of acidic medium. The carbocation formed from given alcohol undergo rearranegement to get stability. Final it loses proton to get an alkene.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a854a3f3-0437-4743-b145-22f9a1c4dccf-926295fe-5d45-488e-b632-a4cb5b40384a-9894605_5.PNG\" style=\"width: 424px; height: 411px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26894,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/56deb696-015b-4a17-ad9a-9258049ecbe5-image.png\" style=\"width: 148px; height: 110px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c84ddd73-2c11-42a1-8710-812737af668c-image.png\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b512a56b-8b2c-4fde-8f3f-59bbebc579fc-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 110px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/61a40133-da21-470b-ada4-2378d0ac7cdf-image.png\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 130px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In first step bromination reaction will take place. Since hydroxy group on benzene is ortho para directing in nature and aldehyde is meta directing in nature. Bromination will take place at ortho position with respect to hydroxy group and at meta position w.r.t. aldehyde group.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/28abba2c-3209-4f41-9033-40fc6007e64f-image.png\" style=\"width: 388px; height: 250px;\" /></p><p>Next aldehyde will react Hydroxylamine to form oxime. This is an example of nucleophilic addition reaction followed by elimination. In last step dehydration reaction will take place which will convert oxime into cyanide.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26817,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II","A-III, B-IV, C-I, D-II","A-I, B-III, C-II, D-IV","A-I, B-II, C-III, D-IV"],"answer":0,"solution":"Cyclohexanol is a secondary alcohol, which gives a positive Lucas test.<br><br>Cyclohexylamine is a primary aliphatic amine, which reacts with Hinsberg's reagent (benzenesulfonyl chloride) to form a product soluble in alkali.<br><br>Cyclohexanecarbaldehyde is an aliphatic aldehyde, which gives a positive Tollen's test (silver mirror test).<br><br>Phenol undergoes the phthalein dye test by reacting with phthalic anhydride in the presence of concentrated sulfuric acid to form phenolphthalein, which gives a pink colour in an alkaline medium.<br><br>Thus, the correct matching is A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II.<br><br>Answer: A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26908,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/efced8a6-fbcd-4f98-b39e-e13763c8bf33-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 123px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fa25e5ff-6d4c-47ae-a569-eff255e3eda6-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/96f05dba-1b83-43fc-806d-896f881bb73a-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 104px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1b72f834-2f18-4210-b7d1-41092326f170-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 99px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Dehydration of alcohols&nbsp;involves the formation of carbocation intermediate and this carbocation&nbsp;rearrange to form more stable carbocation which looses proton to form a more stable alkene.</p><p>In the following dehydration&nbsp;reaction also initially a secondary carbocation is formed which undergoes methyl shift to form a more stable tertiary carbocation which looses proton to form a stable&nbsp;alkene.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5725cc8c-6191-44bb-bab4-8da56054e657-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 229px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26927,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/644e2487-5659-4c2b-94b0-d5ca40d71153-image.png\" style=\"width: 206px; height: 118px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8010b974-804e-4148-89fd-6caf6fe276a2-image.png\" style=\"width: 207px; height: 118px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a58e6d1c-1a5e-4762-a25c-db29faa76c85-image.png\" style=\"width: 168px; height: 139px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c05cce57-3f4f-41e1-8d1a-5a04de24890a-image.png\" style=\"width: 188px; height: 135px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a5ec936f-a572-4eba-87f5-e1d16249b85d-image.png\" style=\"width: 186px; height: 151px;\" /></p><p>Explanation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math>&nbsp;test is used for carbonyl compound (aldehyde <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#38;</mo></math> ketone)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26943,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/759c991b-1c00-4fc2-8cfb-e0c7dbbedb54-image.png\" style=\"width: 175px; height: 115px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/80790ef6-a45b-4b83-84b4-5888a6cdfbe1-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 126px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/996eeb54-353f-4ded-8559-f870b1d660a6-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 115px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e2845a2b-7b7e-4d44-858e-c75982d5f61c-image.png\" style=\"width: 169px; height: 115px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a93c6b41-ef03-40b8-a3cd-98a774843f1b-image.png\" style=\"width: 419px; height: 278px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26878,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Anisole, methyl orange","Salicylaldehyde, Phenolphthalein","Toludine, Phenolphthalein","Carbolic acid, Phenolphthalein"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Carbolic acid or phenol reacts with phthalic anhydride in presence of conc. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;to form phenolphthalein which is used as an acid base indicator. The type of reaction involved is electrophilic substitution reaction. Phenol is ortho-para directing group. Hence, substitution occurs at para position.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/76f483f5-ac8b-4491-8174-953562234bce.png\" style=\"width: 540px; height: 264px;\" /></p><p>The phenolphthalein is colourless below pH 8.5 and attains a pink to deep red hue above pH 9.0.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26844,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["20 .44 g","4.0 g","6.0 g","10.22"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/xxkvvamLRPIjPMlUhpqz4OKkUyD20Fp-qHiOVAh_63w.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\text { Moles of phenol }=\\frac{2}{94}=0.021 \\\\ & \\therefore \\text { Moles of bromine }=0.021 \\times 3=0.064 \\\\ & \\therefore \\text { Mass of bromine }=0.064 \\times 160=10.22 \\mathrm{~g}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26825,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["5","2","4","3"],"answer":2,"solution":"In acetylation, each hydroxyl group reacts:<br>R-OH + (CH₃CO)₂O → R-O-CO-CH₃ + CH₃COOH.<br>Each -OH is converted to -OCOCH₃, resulting in a net mass increase of 42 g/mol per hydroxyl group (addition of acetyl group mass 43, removal of hydrogen mass 1).<br>Given: Original molar mass = 122 g/mol, Product molar mass = 290 g/mol<br>Total mass increase = 290 - 122 = 168 g/mol<br>Number of hydroxyl groups = 168 ÷ 42 = 4","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26880,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/edbccf80-8ad3-423c-a101-0da665bd2a9d-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 105px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ec8fddd7-620e-429b-89c3-0945d2b1698e-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 104px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b4056bc5-46e6-45ed-95e4-1cfa88bd2401-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 107px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9a1f75be-ff78-4aba-b2d9-9e49778233d0-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 185px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The given reaction is an example of dehydration of alcohol. In this reaction the first step is protonation of alcohol which leads to the formation of carbocation. The carbocation formed undergo rearrangement to get stability. The tertiary carbocation formed in this reaction involved in ring closure, which loses proton to from alkene. The steps are shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ca2585c9-5d7d-49a0-9f41-3b1b6b88c8c7-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 343px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26859,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>(A)-(IV), (B)-(II), (C)-(I), (D)-(III) </mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>(A)-(IV), (B)-(I), (C)-(II), (D)-(III) </mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>(A)-(III), (B)-(I), (C)-(II), (D)-(IV) </mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext> (A)-(III), (B)-(IV), (C)-(I), (D)-(II) </mtext></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>(A) When phenol is distilled with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi><mo>-</mo></math>dust, it gives benzene. it is an example of reduction. Phenol loses one <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> atom.</p><p>(B) When phenol is treated with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CHCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math> followed by acidification, salicyaldehyde is formed. The reaction is known as Reimer Tiemann reaction.</p><p>(C) Reaction of phenol with sodium hydroxide and carbon dioxide is Kolbe's Schmidt reaction that is a electrophilic substitution reaction resulting in the formation of salicylic acid as shown in the reaction.</p><p>The major product obtained on interaction of phenol with sodium hydroxide and carbon dioxide is salicylic acid.</p><p>(D) With concentrated nitric acid, phenol is converted to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Trinitrophenol. The product is commonly known as picric acid.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/643e89d4-02ac-4f59-b547-9992eb3da6a5.png\" style=\"width: 471px; height: 544px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26934,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Ethoxy<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl butane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Ethoxy<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl butane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Ethoxy<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl butane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Hydroxy<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl butane"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a848042c-a68c-4e5c-9ec4-46c78ab924d9-image.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 419px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26810,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":1,"solution":"In option (A), the Friedel-Crafts alkylation of benzene with 1-chloropropane involves the formation of a primary carbocation, $CH_3CH_2CH_2^+$. This undergoes a 1,2-hydride shift to form a more stable secondary carbocation, $CH_3CH^+CH_3$, which then attacks the benzene ring to yield cumene. Thus, rearrangement occurs.<br><br>In option (B), the acid-catalyzed dehydration of tert-butyl alcohol proceeds via the formation of a tert-butyl carbocation, $(CH_3)_3C^+$. Since it is already a highly stable tertiary carbocation, it does not undergo any rearrangement and directly loses a proton to form 2-methylpropene.<br><br>In option (C), the isomerization of n-hexane in the presence of anhydrous $AlCl_3$ and $HCl$ proceeds via the formation of carbocations that undergo skeletal rearrangements to form more stable branched isomers like 2-methylpentane.<br><br>In option (D), the acid-catalyzed dehydration of neopentyl alcohol initially forms a primary neopentyl carbocation, $(CH_3)_3CCH_2^+$. This undergoes a 1,2-methyl shift to form a more stable tertiary carbocation, $(CH_3)_2C^+CH_2CH_3$, which then loses a proton to yield 2-methyl-2-butene. Thus, rearrangement occurs.<br><br>Therefore, the reaction in option (B) is the only one where the major product is not obtained by a rearrangement reaction.<br><br>Answer:","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (08 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26992,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Claisen reaction","Schotten-Baumann reaction","Reimer-Tiemann reaction","Gatterman-Koch reaction"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9L8tNRo-P-5HuN-uX_kiJbtSKip-nnsotYk3Wa1mG48.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\"Schotten-Baumann reaction\".","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (23 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26946,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8f3bc87c-373b-4c47-b69b-af42bb6cfa3a-image.png\" style=\"width: 178px; height: 70px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d2f2eaca-c792-4f6c-8ef6-0553caa84a52-image.png\" style=\"width: 188px; height: 73px;\" />","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c6b6142e-5100-4f57-83f5-43335680e9c5-image.png\" style=\"width: 405px; height: 390px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26936,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d1b563ff-a3ac-401b-8a94-4dff22bf44a0-image.png\" style=\"width: 137px; height: 133px;\" />&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/620b9742-1c3b-4987-b574-bcd91f6e4b5f-image.png\" style=\"width: 136px; height: 127px;\" />&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e90aca99-8876-46aa-a19e-8a49f9a73c86-image.png\" style=\"width: 136px; height: 127px;\" />&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/facd0bc5-59d5-48af-b5ee-6773e6f400d2-image.png\" style=\"width: 137px; height: 133px;\" />&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/57dcc4d5-7af1-416c-9f1a-f31adaf9b90b-image.png\" style=\"width: 382px; height: 361px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26970,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/116e0f29-d37b-4cfa-8000-1566281bc1ca-83.jpg\" style=\"width: 376px; height: 109px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/47d44c56-ba90-4c59-8b10-af58fb30197a-80.jpg\" style=\"width: 372px; height: 113px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5d521e8f-1762-4e9e-90e9-3ad229bac528-81.jpg\" style=\"width: 421px; height: 112px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cf31078b-79bb-4624-b9c2-2152d50c89e0-82.jpg\" style=\"width: 448px; height: 86px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/266681.jpg\" style=\"width: 346px; height: 116px;\" /><br />This step involves acid-base reaction at first followed by nucleophilic addition elimination.<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/266681_1.jpg\" style=\"width: 263px; height: 141px;\" /><br />This step is called bromination.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":26838,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/NREl5cnyhDv8c9GmO5LM5yMsSeKAU4n2tzaXhq2beCw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />Phenolic group soluble in NaOH<br>Benzaldehyde derivative react with Tollen's reagent.<br>Vanillin does not give self-aldol reaction due to lack of acidic H for condensation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26959,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1cb909aa-f53f-4455-8ea7-899395b9e1e0-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 141px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/904b7d00-ef43-4309-9f47-4b0cb715297a-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 154px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/efa74e35-0bfe-4161-af7e-c87e071b949c-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 170px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aa9a8883-2d12-4f21-b554-a85002a73b5a-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 159px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"(i) phenol gives test with neutral <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>.<br />(ii) aldehyde gives Fehling test.<br />(iii) <img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/85e33833-fa68-4cbd-a319-be7137370187-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 109px;\" /> group gives iodoform test.<br />(iv) Grignard reagent gives test with acidic hydrogen.<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c254a333-89d2-4fd3-af67-cf4482a314e8-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 157px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26815,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; width: auto;\"><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">D</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">E</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">Conc. H$_2$SO$_4$</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">CH$_2 =$ CH $-$ CH(OH)CH$_3$</td></tr></table>","<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; width: auto;\"><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">D</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">E</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">PCC</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">HO $-$ CH$_2$ $-$ CH$_2$ $-$ CH $=$ CH$_2$</td></tr></table>","<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; width: auto;\"><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">D</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">E</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">PCC</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">CH$_2 =$ CH $-$ CH $=$ CH$_2$</td></tr></table>","<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; width: auto;\"><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">D</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">E</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">Conc. H$_2$SO$_4$ or H$_3$PO$_4$</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">CH$_2 =$ CH $-$ CH $=$ CH$_2$</td></tr></table>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Compound A is pentan-1-ol ($CH_3-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-OH$) and Compound B is pent-1-ene ($CH_2=CH-CH_2-CH_2-CH_3$).<br><br>The conversion of an alcohol to an alkene is a dehydration reaction, which requires an acidic dehydrating agent such as concentrated $H_2SO_4$ or $H_3PO_4$. Thus, reagent D is concentrated $H_2SO_4$ or $H_3PO_4$.<br><br>Compound C is butane-1,3-diol ($HO-CH_2-CH_2-CH(OH)-CH_3$).<br><br>When C is treated with excess dehydrating agent (reagent D), both hydroxyl groups undergo elimination (dehydration). The elimination of two water molecules yields a conjugated diene, which is highly stable due to resonance.<br><br>The product E formed is 1,3-butadiene ($CH_2=CH-CH=CH_2$).<br><br>Answer: <table style=\"border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; width: auto;\"><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">D</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">E</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">Conc. H$_2$SO$_4$ or H$_3$PO$_4$</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">CH$_2 =$ CH $-$ CH $=$ CH$_2$</td></tr></table>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26999,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["2-Butanone","Ethyl chloride","Ethyl ethanoate","Diethyl ether"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cg90HL3mPvsT94ppf46L7vPOnnB0NCJM1wzyeobvsYo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":26919,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false.","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true.","Both Statement I and Statement II are true."],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math>Mixture of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CO</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is called water gas or syn gas<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math>Syn gas is produced by coal gasification <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><mn>1270</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow></mover><mi>CO</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26951,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fe5962b2-177f-4ac5-bcfd-fe9f0382dbfe.png\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/33f36970-ea31-49bd-8dbc-34feda6c1010.png\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/48600a74-1343-4e30-b546-866c5e1c23b5.png\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/79ad7c7a-985a-4dad-8018-bef7d8f836b1.png\">"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a2520a18-03a4-4b1e-82f2-042d2354ec95.png\">","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26928,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/49963bfd-4331-4a68-b53c-552781c4b4f7-image.png\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 159px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cdfb6695-5b7f-4a7b-b757-dd6a33c95ae8-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 156px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2e9b82c2-bdee-4a7b-88d8-1fa0e256eb24-image.png\" style=\"width: 149px; height: 160px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7191b163-4fba-4e79-9605-7c046f04e218-image.png\" style=\"width: 152px; height: 150px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/40007081-f087-4e74-ba8e-f53dda9bb10c-image.png\" style=\"width: 478px; height: 277px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27010,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["acetone","acetyl iodide","2- methyl -2-propanol","acetamide"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":26839,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0OysscCR70UVRM7lgL6zfe5cjnl6Vbnw_dExYi6U57c.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/iiErfwUmZcJVaDvZOJQdxwHBp_Ic5tYyrljWcSI75qA.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Tz3S-uachaYcxYGyZMAkp8XMC8LsjixhG6FoawmsVMc.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/GCAX5lPGOTZDLfnPeLWEmIJ3Qip0rzKdEN5Tzh5AOow.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0A2gDcH2nP2C5WuGWWBHicWn7z7nCwuzffQ4MVPHQoM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26906,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3ac36514-03a9-4575-be40-178113cd1019-image.png\" style=\"width: 105px; height: 80px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9814d91f-55ac-4c7d-8a30-c1aa4b67be39-image.png\" style=\"width: 106px; height: 80px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/50b455d1-aeaf-4858-86fd-e0a02227442c-image.png\" style=\"width: 172px; height: 90px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f1ce1beb-8de4-4442-b501-880fffc7fadd-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 80px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1d7e193e-8a4e-420e-9f34-ebb5c4115c4d-17768a9e-df81-4461-ac55-6f8b7a36b526-image.png\" style=\"width: 836px; height: 149px;\" /></p><p>In first step acid base reaction with substitution reaction will take place.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26877,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>PhO</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeOH</mi></math>","Benzene, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MeBr</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ph</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>MeO</mi><mo>&#8854;</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>PhO</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeBr</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The given methyl phenyl ether can be prepared from&nbsp;Williamson Ether Synthesis.&nbsp;Williamson Ether Synthesis usually takes place as an <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> reaction of a Alkyl halide with an alkoxide ion. Aryl halides cannot be used in this reaction. The reaction is given below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cabe1b84-ce1a-42a8-8133-d132c3aebf8d.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 83px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26828,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["(i) \\(\\mathrm{NaOH}(\\mathrm{aq})\\); $\\ \\ \\ $ (ii) Jones reagent; (iii) $\\ \\ \\ $ \\(\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}\\)","(i) \\(\\mathrm{B}_2 \\mathrm{H}_6 / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}_2\\); $\\ \\ \\ $ (ii) NaOEt; $\\ \\ \\ $ (iii) Jones reagent","(i) Jones reagent; $\\ \\ \\ $ (ii) NaOEt; $\\ \\ \\ $ (iii) \\(\\mathrm{Hot} \\mathrm{KMnO}_4 / \\mathrm{KOH}\\)","(i) NaOEt; $\\ \\ \\ $ (ii) \\(\\mathrm{B}_2 \\mathrm{H}_6 / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}_2\\); $\\ \\ \\ $ (iii) Jones reagent"],"answer":3,"solution":"The transformation of (X) benzene with Br and CH₃ substituents to (Y) benzene with CH₂COOH requires:<br>First, NaOEt causes elimination of HBr to form an alkene intermediate.<br>Second, B₂H₆/H₂O₂ performs hydroboration-oxidation, adding hydroxyl group in anti-Markovnikov fashion to yield a primary alcohol.<br>Third, Jones reagent oxidizes the primary alcohol to carboxylic acid.<br>The sequence NaOEt → B₂H₆/H₂O₂ → Jones reagent produces the desired carboxylic acid product.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26849,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_A_IEc75Rex1r9xL6yvWc_4hyhGCd-m7J_s4lT-6GeI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8j7AP9WwVOmxq75tiikT3cplI8ZHNarWxpaH_gGCGCA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Mg2m7JEoOsyo9_PguLarVQLO1td8D9YIbHgvSsWWU4g.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EXMHPqo-HSppoQen4oVJEKGbbHEyJRc4UeVoSWvd1go.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/MX4sW3QFSL4Mmytfy2KNgfMo0_YYLCow6aw3Eri_2MU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26980,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Nucleophilic substitution","Electrophilic addition","Nucleophilic addition","Electrophilic substitution"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The&nbsp;Williamson&nbsp;ether&nbsp;synthesis&nbsp;is the most widely used method to synthesize ethers. It occurs by an <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> reaction in which a metal alkoxide displaces a halide ion from an alkyl halide.<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mtext>RO</mtext><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mtext>R</mtext><mo>&#39;</mo></msup><mo>-</mo><mtext>x</mtext><munder><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mtext>S</mtext><mtext>N</mtext></msub></munder><mtext>R</mtext><mo>-</mo><mtext>O</mtext><mo>-</mo><msup><mtext>R</mtext><mo>&#39;</mo></msup></math><br /><br />This is Nucleophilic substitution reaction.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null}]